The FE-SEM images and representative EDS analysis were provided for resultant samples to determining the shape and elemental structure. The FE-SEM images for resultant nanocomposites show the nanostructures with morphology of rods which affected with carbonous compounds. Fig. 4
                        (a, b) is related to the GO based nanocomposites. Dimeter size range for rods in S1 is 46–157 nm. Fig. 4(c, d) confirms the presence of GQDs in the composite texture due to the change in the surface of rods. The GQDs has the gummy form which cover the surface of nanorods. Fig. 4(e, f) is correlated to the MWCNTs based nanocomposites and the presence of carbon nanotubes in the composite texture can be established. Diameter range size for S3 is 40–190 nm. Additionally, the EDS analysis (Fig. 5
                        ) for all samples present the elemental structure with existence of Co, N, V, C and O.

The BET measurement was conducted at 196 °C using a Tristar 3000 automated gas adsorption analyzer from Micromeritics. The pore size distribution was measured using the BJH method and the desorption branch of the isotherm. The surface properties of the nanostructured materials that resulted were examined using the N2 adsorption-desorption (BET-BJH) method under the identical conditions (Fig. 7
                        ). The process of hydrogen adsorption and insertion into pores or onto surfaces is highly dependent on surface properties and porosity. Therefore, it is possible to use active materials with the right amount of porosity for energy storage. According to the IUPAC classification, resultant BET hysteresis for resultant composites exhibits hysteresis of type H3 and adsorption isotherms of type IV. This indicates the presence of solid structures with mesopores and slit pores with non-uniform size distribution. The findings of the BET studies of resultant composite are summarized in Table 1
                        . The MWCNTs based nanocomposites show higher surface area (17.155 m2g−1) than other composites. Lower surface area (5.0257 m2g−1) is related to the GO based nanocomposites.
